---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import TimingHistogram from "../components/charts/TimingHistogram";
import EngagementScatter from "../components/charts/EngagementScatter";
import RecapChart from "../components/charts/RecapChart";
---

<Layout title="Report">
  <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-6 py-16">
    <header class="mb-16 animate-in">
      <h1 class="text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight mb-4 leading-tight">What Separates Winners from Everyone Else?</h1>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground text-lg">A data analysis across three Figma × Contra Makeathon editions — June 2026</p>
    </header>

    <section class="mb-16 animate-in animate-in-delay-1">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-foreground">The Pattern — And Where It Breaks</h2>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4">
        After analyzing <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">276 scraped posts</strong> across three editions,
        the picture is more nuanced than expected. Engagement predicted winning in March 2026
        — Lee Black's Airwwave entry had <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">4.2× more likes</strong> than the
        average non-winner. But in Config 2026, the $50K grand prize went to a post with only 23 likes
        while non-winners averaged 83. What changed? The judging criteria expanded to include a
        dedicated "Build In Public" category.
      </p>
      <ul class="space-y-2 text-muted-foreground ml-4">
        <li>March 2026 engagement gap: <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">4.2×</strong> more likes for confirmed winner vs non-winner avg</li>
        <li>Config 2026 social presence: <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">2.2 vs 0</strong> avg platforms cross-posted (winners vs non-winners)</li>
        <li>Video presence across editions: <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">85%+</strong> of Config 2026 winners included a video demo</li>
        <li>Lee Black won twice: <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Airwwave</strong> (March 2026) and <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Connected Earth</strong> (Config 2026)</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-6 text-foreground animate-in">Edition-by-Edition Breakdown</h2>
      <div class="mb-10 animate-in animate-in-delay-1">
        <h3 class="font-semibold mb-3">Figma Make-a-thon (Sep 3–10, 2025)</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
          $100K prize pool. Submissions were posted as replies to announcement threads — a link-drop model
          with minimal engagement signal. Engagement data is unavailable for this edition.
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-border">
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th class="text-right">Winners</th><th class="text-right">Non-Winners</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Entries Captured</td><td class="text-right">1 confirmed</td><td class="text-right">242</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Avg Post Day</td><td class="text-right">Day 9</td><td class="text-right">Day 9.9</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Engagement (Likes)</td><td class="text-right" colspan="2">Not available — link-drop submission model</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Social Cross-Posts</td><td class="text-right" colspan="2">Not tracked in thread replies</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Submission Format</td><td class="text-right" colspan="2">Replies to announcement post (no direct Contra feed)</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground mt-2">
          Note: Sep 2025 used a reply-thread model; posts did not appear in the Contra tag feed and engagement counts were not tracked.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="mb-10 animate-in animate-in-delay-2">
        <h3 class="font-semibold mb-3">Figma Makeathon March 2026 (Feb 1 – Mar 16)</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
          $100K prize pool. Six categories. 21 posts scraped from the dedicated tag feed; 17 enriched with real engagement data.
          Only Lee Black's Airwwave entry was confirmed among the top-scraped set.
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-border">
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th class="text-right">Winner (Lee Black)</th><th class="text-right">Non-Winners (20)</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Entries with Engagement Data</td><td class="text-right">1 / 6 winners</td><td class="text-right">17 / 20</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Avg Post Day</td><td class="text-right">Day 29</td><td class="text-right">Day 33.6</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Avg Likes</td><td class="text-right">222</td><td class="text-right">52.6</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Engagement Multiplier</td><td class="text-right">4.2×</td><td class="text-right">—</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Project</td><td class="text-right">Airwwave (ambient music)</td><td class="text-right">—</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="mb-10 animate-in animate-in-delay-3">
        <h3 class="font-semibold mb-3">Config Makeathon 2026 (Jun 4–18)</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground mb-3">
          $100K prize pool. Six categories including "Build In Public." 13 posts scraped; all 6 winner entries
          fetched individually with real engagement counts.
        </p>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-xl border border-border">
          <table>
            <thead><tr><th>Metric</th><th class="text-right">Winners (6)</th><th class="text-right">Non-Winners (13)</th></tr></thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Entries</td><td class="text-right">6</td><td class="text-right">13</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Avg Post Day</td><td class="text-right">Day 13.2</td><td class="text-right">Day 14.9</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Avg Likes</td><td class="text-right">76.5</td><td class="text-right">83.0</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Avg Social Platforms</td><td class="text-right">2.2</td><td class="text-right">0.0</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="font-medium">Grand Prize Winner Likes</td><td class="text-right">23 (Bene Brandhofer)</td><td class="text-right">Top non-winner: 149</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground mt-2">
          The $50K Grand Prize went to Bene Brandhofer's "Visual Atlas" with only 23 likes.
          Angelo Pacaanas led with 149 likes but did not place. Social cross-posting was the stronger predictor.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-foreground animate-in">The Timing Effect</h2>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4 animate-in animate-in-delay-1">
        Timing data (days into the submission window) is available for all 276 entries.
        Sep 2025 and Config 2026 show no meaningful timing gap between winners and non-winners.
        In March 2026, Lee Black posted around <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Day 29</strong> of a 44-day window —
        relatively late, suggesting that in longer contests, timing matters less than quality.
      </p>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-border p-6 bg-card animate-in animate-in-delay-2">
        <TimingHistogram client:load />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-foreground animate-in">The Social Multiplier</h2>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4 animate-in animate-in-delay-1">
        In Config 2026, winners cross-posted to an average of <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">2.2 platforms</strong>
        compared to 0 for non-winners in the scraped set. Halle Clark (Build In Public winner)
        cross-posted to <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">4 platforms</strong> despite having only 8 likes —
        suggesting judges valued consistent social presence over peak engagement.
      </p>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-border p-6 bg-card animate-in animate-in-delay-2">
        <EngagementScatter client:load />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-16">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-foreground animate-in">The Engagement Paradox</h2>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4 animate-in animate-in-delay-1">
        Config 2026 flipped the engagement narrative. Non-winners averaged <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">83 likes</strong>
        versus <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">76.5</strong> for winners. The grand prize went to Visual Atlas (23 likes)
        while Connected Earth (156 likes) won a $10K category. Engagement predicts visibility, not judging outcomes.
        The <strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Build In Public</strong> category explicitly rewarded consistency
        and community involvement — a different signal than peak likes.
      </p>
      <div class="rounded-xl border border-border p-6 bg-card animate-in animate-in-delay-2">
        <RecapChart client:load />
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-16 animate-in">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold mb-4 text-foreground">What This Means for Participants</h2>
      <p class="text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The data across three editions suggests different strategies for different goals:
      </p>
      <ol class="space-y-3 text-muted-foreground ml-4 list-decimal">
        <li><strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Build something genuinely interesting</strong> — Bene Brandhofer's 23-like entry beat a 149-like entry for the grand prize</li>
        <li><strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Cross-post everywhere for Build In Public categories</strong> — 2.2 avg platforms vs 0 is a stark gap</li>
        <li><strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Include a video demo</strong> — all Config 2026 winners had video; 85%+ across the edition</li>
        <li><strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Engage with the community</strong> — Lee Black won in both March and June with very different projects but consistent community presence</li>
        <li><strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Read the judging criteria for each edition</strong> — as new categories emerge (Build In Public, Innovative Workflow), the winning formula shifts</li>
        <li><strong class="text-foreground font-semibold">Come back for the next one</strong> — Lee Black is the only two-time winner in this dataset</li>
      </ol>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-8 rounded-2xl border border-border p-6 bg-card animate-in">
      <h2 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-3">Data Notes</h2>
      <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed mb-2">
        276 posts scraped from Contra's GraphQL API across 3 editions. Sep 2025 submissions were
        posted as replies to announcement threads (not in the tag feed); engagement data is unavailable.
        March 2026: 17/21 scraped entries have real API engagement data; 5 of 6 winners' entries were
        not in the top-21 scrape. Config 2026: 13 scraped from the tag feed; 6 winner posts fetched
        individually from their direct Contra URLs.
      </p>
      <p class="text-sm text-muted-foreground">
        Config 2026 winners were announced at Config on June 23, 2026. Sep 2025 winner: Cara Ellis
        (Web Poetry, $50K). March 2026 winners include Lee Black (Airwwave), Charlota Blunárová
        (Common Thread), Kiel Cole (TOKYO), Aleyna Çatak (Pucker), Paige Latimer (Duet Booth),
        Dann Petty (Reframe It).
      </p>
    </section>
  </article>
</Layout>
